solution:
First, notice that all three integers have a common factor of 10.  We can remove this factor from the cube root as shown: \begin{align*}
\sqrt[3]{10^3\cdot3^3+10^3\cdot4^3+10^3\cdot5^3}&=\sqrt[3]{10^3(3^3+4^3+5^3)}\\
&=10\sqrt[3]{3^3+4^3+5^3}.
\end{align*} Now, evaluate the expression under the cube root: $$10\sqrt[3]{3^3+4^3+5^3}=10\sqrt[3]{27+64+125}=10\sqrt[3]{216}.$$ Since $216=6^3$, this expression simplifies to: $$10\sqrt[3]{6^3}=\boxed{60}.$$
chatgpt_solution: We can rewrite the expression under the cube root as $(30^3+40^3+50^3)^{\frac{1}{3}}$. Since $30$, $40$, and $50$ are all multiples of $10$, we can factor out $10^3$ from each term: $$(30^3+40^3+50^3)^{\frac{1}{3}}=(10^3\cdot3^3+10^3\cdot4^3+10^3\cdot5^3)^{\frac{1}{3}}.$$We can factor out $10^3$ from the cube root: $$\left(10^3(3^3+4^3+5^3)\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}.$$Applying the properties of exponents, we have $$(10^3)^{\frac{1}{3}} \cdot (3^3+4^3+5^3)^{\frac{1}{3}}.$$Since $a^{\frac{1}{n}}=\sqrt[n]{a}$, we can "cancel" the exponents: $$10^1 \cdot (3^3+4^3+5^3)^{\frac{1}{3}}=10\sqrt[3]{3^3+4^3+5^3}.$$Thus, the simplified expression is $\boxed{10\sqrt[3]{3^3+4^3+5^3}}$.
